\begin_layout Subsection
Attitude Convention Combinations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Three (spin) angle values, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \xi_{1},\xi_{2},\xi_{3}\right\} $
\end_inset

, are available and known to associate with the three rotation parameters,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\alpha,\beta,\gamma\right]$
\end_inset

, but it is not known in what order they correspond.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is assumed that unitary bivectors, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

, correspond with coordinate system basis planes, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ e_{23,}e_{31},e_{12}\right\} $
\end_inset

, but again the association and order are unknown.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition there is ambiguity in the chirality of the orientation for each
 individual rotation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These possibilities can be expressed as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Create a collection of sign signatures 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \pm,\pm,\pm\right\} $
\end_inset

 that may be applied to the angle sizes.
 There are 8 unique signatures:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ ---,\,--+,\,-+-,\,-++,\,+--,\,+-+,\,++-,\,+++\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Create a collection of combinations of angle size values from 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \xi_{1},\xi_{2},\xi_{3}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The 6 non trivial cases include combintations of all three available data
 values that may be assigned to the angle sizes, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \alpha,\beta,\gamma\right\} $
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ \xi_{1}\xi_{2}\xi_{3},\,\xi_{1}\xi_{3}\xi_{2},\,\xi_{2}\xi_{3}\xi_{1},\,\xi_{2}\xi_{1}\xi_{3},\,\xi_{3}\xi_{1}\xi_{2},\,\xi_{3}\xi_{2}\xi_{1}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Create a collection of basis vector (positive) directions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ X,Y,Z\right\} $
\end_inset

, where each letter denotes one of the coordinate system basis planes, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ e_{23},e_{31},e_{12}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Note that negative directions are not needed here since the plane direction
 is coupled directly with the sign on the angle size.
 Overall the combinations correspond with a 3-digit base three number for
 which there are 27 exhaustive cases.
 There of these, three cases can be eliminated as physically trivial.
 This leaves the 24 basis plane combinations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left\{ \cancel{XXX},\,XXY,\,XXZ\right\} \\
\left\{ XYX,\,XYY,\,XYZ\right\} \\
\left\{ XZX,\,XZY,\,XZZ\right\} 
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left\{ YXX,\,YXY,\,YXZ\right\} \\
\left\{ YYX,\,\cancel{YYY},\,YYZ\right\} \\
\left\{ YZX,\,YZY,\,YZZ\right\} 
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left\{ ZXX,\,ZXY,\,ZXZ\right\} \\
\left\{ ZYX,\,ZYY,\,ZYZ\right\} \\
\left\{ ZZX,\,ZZY,\,\cancel{ZZZ}\right\} 
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Overall, these cases represent 
\begin_inset Formula $1152=8*6*24$
\end_inset

 candidate conventions for combining the attitude parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Offset Convention Combinations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The offset of each sensor may be expressed by a vector with three components
 relative to a Cartesian frame basis, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ e_{1},e_{2},e_{3}\right\} .$
\end_inset

 E.g.,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t=\tau_{1}e_{1}+\tau_{2}e_{2}+\tau_{3}e_{3}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume three parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \zeta_{1},\zeta_{2},\zeta_{3}\right\} $
\end_inset

 are given that describe this offset (aka lever arm, eccentricity vector,
 etc) but in an unknown manner, there are several candidate combinations
 to consider.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Create a collection of sign signatures 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \pm,\pm,\pm\right\} $
\end_inset

 that may be applied to the angle sizes.
 There are 8 unique signatures:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ ---,\,--+,\,-+-,\,-++,\,+--,\,+-+,\,++-,\,+++\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Create a collection of candidate coordinate associations 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \zeta_{1},\zeta_{2},\zeta_{3}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The 6 non trivial cases that each include all three combinations of data
 values that may be assigned to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \tau_{1}\tau_{2}\tau_{3}\right\} $
\end_inset

 components of vector, 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ \zeta_{1}\zeta_{2}\zeta_{3},\,\zeta_{1}\zeta_{3}\zeta_{2},\,\zeta_{2}\zeta_{3}\zeta_{1},\,\zeta_{2}\zeta_{1}\zeta_{3},\,\zeta_{3}\zeta_{1}\zeta_{2},\,\zeta_{3}\zeta_{2}\zeta_{1}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Overall, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $48=8*6$
\end_inset

 combinations to consider.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Transform Conventions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A general rigid body transformation may be expressed as a combination of
 translation and rotation.
 Let the rotation be represented by unitary spinor 
\begin_inset Formula $R=e^{\alpha A}e^{\beta B}e^{\gamma C}$
\end_inset

, and translation by the vector, 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A canonical form for the overall exterior orientation is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

translate then rotate
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 convention,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y=R\left(x-t_{x}\right)R^{\dagger}
\]

\end_inset

In this convention, both the translation, 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, and rotation, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, entities are expressed with respect to the transformation domain (e.g.
 domain of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, it is common to also utilize a hybrid domain convention
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y+t_{y}=RxR^{\dagger}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are therefore 2 conventions to consider, 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{y}$
\end_inset

, that must be considered for all of the above combinations of rotations
 and offsets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Overall, there are 1152 attitude conventions, 48 offset conventions, and
 2 transformation conventions, for a total of 
\begin_inset Formula $110,592=1152*48*2$
\end_inset

 total orientation conventions to explore.
\end_layout

